thread.title: Memphis Tigers move up to No. 22 in football coaches poll
thread.title_full: Memphis Tigers move up to No. 22 in football coaches poll

author: Tom Schad
title: Memphis Tigers move up to No. 22 in football coaches poll
text:
When the University of Memphis football team hosts Ole Miss at Liberty Bowl Memorial Stadium on Saturday, only 10 spots will separate them in one of college football’s two major polls.
The Tigers climbed three spots to No. 22 in this week’s Amway Coaches Poll, which is voted upon by a group of 64 Football Bowl Subdivision coaches and was released Sunday morning. For a second consecutive week, Memphis was the only American Athletic Conference team in the group. Houston and Temple finished just outside the coaches’ Top 25 with 75 and 71 votes, respectively.
Memphis narrowly missed a Top 25 ranking in the second major poll, which is arranged by the Associated Press. The Tigers received 59 votes and finished just two spots out of the Top 25. Houston was ranked No. 24, and Temple received 96 votes to finish 26th.
Memphis broke into the coaches poll last week at No. 25 after a 24-17 victory at South Florida, its 12th consecutive win. The next day, coach Justin Fuente said the team would not pay attention to such accolades.
“We have an incredible challenge against an incredibly talented Ole Miss team, and then like I said, six days later, we have to turn around and take it on the road and play a Tulsa team that’s in the Top 5 in the country in scoring and is throwing and running it all over the place,” Fuente said last Monday. “So we don’t have time to sit around and pat each other on the back. We’ve got a lot of work to do.”
The Tigers, who were idle last week, are among the 16 unbeaten teams remaining in the FBS. They have not lost in a full calendar year.
The Rebels checked in at No. 12 in the coaches poll and No. 13 in the AP Top 25 after crushing New Mexico State, 52-3, on Saturday.
